{"questionId":"22773","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following table shows the time, in days, from December <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mtext>st</mtext></math> and the percentage of&nbsp;Christmas trees in stock at a shop on the beginning of that day.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/4347a5b4532501456e415959de70781cdf1714e0.png\"></p>\n<p>The following table shows the natural logarithm of both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> on these days to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> decimal places.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/d9c1e84559f9160aee5a7183a9f3a0e299a209df.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use the data in the second table to find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> and the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> for the&nbsp;regression line, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mi>d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>695</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>695383</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>62974</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22773","referenceCode":"21N.1.AHL.TZ0.12a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Use the data in the second table to find the value of m and the value of b for the regression line, ln x=m(ln d)+b.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.13—Non-linear regression","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.10—Scaling large numbers, log-log graphs"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}